<section id=3D"3.-How-is-this-Bayesian-Network-representing-the-Joint-Distr=
ibution-over-the-variables-?">
<h3>3. How is this Bayesian Network representing the Joint Distribution ove=
r the variables ?<a class=3D"headerlink" href=3D"https://pgmpy.org/detailed=
_notebooks/2.%20Bayesian%20Networks.html#3.-How-is-this-Bayesian-Network-re=
presenting-the-Joint-Distribution-over-the-variables-?" title=3D"Link to th=
is heading">=C2=B6</a></h3>
<p>Till now we just have been considering that the Bayesian Network can rep=
resent the Joint Distribution without any proof. Now let=E2=80=99s see how =
to compute the Joint Distribution from the Bayesian Network.</p>
<p>From the chain rule of probabiliy we know that:</p>
<p><img class=3D"math" src=3D"https://pgmpy.org/_images/math/450c269d6c8455=
37545dd959884402b387796026.png" alt=3D"P(A, B) =3D P(A | B) * P(B)"></p>
<p>Now in this case:</p>
<p><img class=3D"math" src=3D"https://pgmpy.org/_images/math/73145d1c9f34a4=
4c8345b173d43a86d60fb2fd83.png" alt=3D"P(D, I, G, L, S) =3D P(L| S, G, D, I=
) * P(S | G, D, I) * P(G | D, I) * P(D | I) * P(I)"></p>
<p>Applying the local independence conditions in the above equation we will=
 get:</p>
<p><img class=3D"math" src=3D"https://pgmpy.org/_images/math/ce65c955d31210=
4eba537667c12b412f748ad0fc.png" alt=3D"P(D, I, G, L, S) =3D P(L|G) * P(S|I)=
 * P(G| D, I) * P(D) * P(I)"></p>
<p>From the above equation we can clearly see that the Joint Distribution o=
ver all the variables is just the product of all the CPDs in the network. H=
ence encoding the independencies in the Joint Distribution in a graph struc=
ture helped us in reducing the number of parameters that we need to store.<=
/p>
</section>
<section id=3D"4.-Inference-in-Bayesian-Models">
<h3>4. Inference in Bayesian Models<a class=3D"headerlink" href=3D"https://=
pgmpy.org/detailed_notebooks/2.%20Bayesian%20Networks.html#4.-Inference-in-=
Bayesian-Models" title=3D"Link to this heading">=C2=B6</a></h3>
<p>Till now we discussed just about representing Bayesian Networks. Now let=
=E2=80=99s see how we can do inference in a Bayesian Model and use it to pr=
edict values over new data points for machine learning tasks. In this secti=
on we will consider that we already have our model. We will talk about cons=
tructing the models from data in later parts of this tutorial.</p>
<p>In inference we try to answer probability queries over the network given=
 some other variables. So, we might want to know the probable grade of an i=
ntelligent student in a difficult class given that he scored good in SAT. S=
o for computing these values from a Joint Distribution we will have to redu=
ce over the given variables that is <img class=3D"math" src=3D"https://pgmp=
y.org/_images/math/56638e7b194559cee95d15075181eb822168b3a2.png" alt=3D"I =
=3D 1">, <img class=3D"math" src=3D"https://pgmpy.org/_images/math/5374518f=
03c8d128ff8f24fbdfd5b7c9f1d4b620.png" alt=3D"D =3D 1">, <img class=3D"math"=
 src=3D"https://pgmpy.org/_images/math/eb222ef3dc7369b0c714b6c54dd7b5b8fde5=
32d6.png" alt=3D"S =3D 1"> and then marginalize over the other variables th=
at is <img class=3D"math" src=3D"https://pgmpy.org/_images/math/19eef1966f7=
c545af3ac8c0fa486974d873e3c65.png" alt=3D"L"> to get <img class=3D"math" sr=
c=3D"https://pgmpy.org/_images/math/6860587a7759f58e9c25a8ff9e4292766d09adc=
2.png" alt=3D"P(G | I=3D1, D=3D1, S=3D1)">. But carrying on
marginalize and reduce operation on the complete Joint Distribution is comp=
utationaly expensive since we need to iterate over the whole table for each=
 operation and the table is exponential is size to the number of variables.=
 But in Graphical Models we exploit the independencies to break these opera=
tions in smaller parts making it much faster.</p>
<p>One of the very basic methods of inference in Graphical Models is <stron=
g>Variable Elimination</strong>.</p>
<section id=3D"Variable-Elimination">
<h4>Variable Elimination<a class=3D"headerlink" href=3D"https://pgmpy.org/d=
etailed_notebooks/2.%20Bayesian%20Networks.html#Variable-Elimination" title=
=3D"Link to this heading">=C2=B6</a></h4>
<p>We know that:</p>
<p><img class=3D"math" src=3D"https://pgmpy.org/_images/math/9d45568f6d9843=
178bb9623abf8cfa32d70d7017.png" alt=3D"P(D, I, G, L, S) =3D P(L|G) * P(S|I)=
 * P(G|D, I) * P(D) * P(I)"></p>
<p>Now let=E2=80=99s say we just want to compute the probability of G. For =
that we will need to marginalize over all the other variables.</p>
<p><img class=3D"math" src=3D"https://pgmpy.org/_images/math/25efb2436d56df=
876a9b2a79fa67ff39d11b64c2.png" alt=3D"P(G) =3D \sum_{D, I, L, S} P(D, I, G=
, L, S)"></p>
<p><img class=3D"math" src=3D"https://pgmpy.org/_images/math/e817758e2c4be9=
53d3e567e2488a9db200624643.png" alt=3D"P(G) =3D \sum_{D, I, L, S} P(L|G) * =
P(S|I) * P(G|D, I) * P(D) * P(I)"></p>
<p><img class=3D"math" src=3D"https://pgmpy.org/_images/math/6d05237bc63874=
a81b43e526991e4f8b60d1fec4.png" alt=3D"P(G) =3D \sum_D \sum_I \sum_L \sum_S=
 P(L|G) * P(S|I) * P(G|D, I) * P(D) * P(I)"></p>
<p>Now since not all the conditional distributions depend on all the variab=
les we can push the summations inside:</p>
<p><img class=3D"math" src=3D"https://pgmpy.org/_images/math/6d05237bc63874=
a81b43e526991e4f8b60d1fec4.png" alt=3D"P(G) =3D \sum_D \sum_I \sum_L \sum_S=
 P(L|G) * P(S|I) * P(G|D, I) * P(D) * P(I)"></p>
<p><img class=3D"math" src=3D"https://pgmpy.org/_images/math/2ed151c5fa794c=
d5a7371b21a9fab6c2cd5ed9e6.png" alt=3D"P(G) =3D \sum_D P(D) \sum_I P(G|D, I=
) * P(I) \sum_S P(S|I) \sum_L P(L|G)"></p>
<p>So, by pushing the summations inside we have saved a lot of computation =
because we have to now iterate over much smaller tables.</p>
<p>Let=E2=80=99s take an example for inference using Variable Elimination i=
n pgmpy:</p>
<div class=3D"nbinput docutils container">
<div class=3D"prompt highlight-none notranslate"><div class=3D"highlight"><=
pre id=3D"codecell50"><span></span>[52]:
</pre><button class=3D"copybtn o-tooltip--left" data-tooltip=3D"Copy" data-=
clipboard-target=3D"#codecell50">
      <svg xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class=3D"icon icon-tabler i=
con-tabler-copy" width=3D"44" height=3D"44" viewBox=3D"0 0 24 24" stroke-wi=
dth=3D"1.5" stroke=3D"#000000" fill=3D"none" stroke-linecap=3D"round" strok=
e-linejoin=3D"round">
  <title>Copy to clipboard</title>
  <path stroke=3D"none" d=3D"M0 0h24v24H0z" fill=3D"none"></path>
  <rect x=3D"8" y=3D"8" width=3D"12" height=3D"12" rx=3D"2"></rect>
  <path d=3D"M16 8v-2a2 2 0 0 0 -2 -2h-8a2 2 0 0 0 -2 2v8a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h2">=
</path>
</svg>
    </button></div>
</div>
<div class=3D"input_area highlight-ipython3 notranslate"><div class=3D"high=
light"><pre id=3D"codecell51"><span></span><span class=3D"kn">from</span><s=
pan class=3D"w"> </span><span class=3D"nn">pgmpy.inference</span><span clas=
s=3D"w"> </span><span class=3D"kn">import</span> <span class=3D"n">Variable=
Elimination</span>
<span class=3D"n">infer</span> <span class=3D"o">=3D</span> <span class=3D"=
n">VariableElimination</span><span class=3D"p">(</span><span class=3D"n">mo=
del</span><span class=3D"p">)</span>
<span class=3D"n">g_dist</span> <span class=3D"o">=3D</span> <span class=3D=
"n">infer</span><span class=3D"o">.</span><span class=3D"n">query</span><sp=
an class=3D"p">([</span><span class=3D"s1">'G'</span><span class=3D"p">])</=
span>
<span class=3D"nb">print</span><span class=3D"p">(</span><span class=3D"n">=
g_dist</span><span class=3D"p">)</span>
</pre><button class=3D"copybtn o-tooltip--left" data-tooltip=3D"Copy" data-=
clipboard-target=3D"#codecell51">
      <svg xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class=3D"icon icon-tabler i=
con-tabler-copy" width=3D"44" height=3D"44" viewBox=3D"0 0 24 24" stroke-wi=
dth=3D"1.5" stroke=3D"#000000" fill=3D"none" stroke-linecap=3D"round" strok=
e-linejoin=3D"round">
  <title>Copy to clipboard</title>
  <path stroke=3D"none" d=3D"M0 0h24v24H0z" fill=3D"none"></path>
  <rect x=3D"8" y=3D"8" width=3D"12" height=3D"12" rx=3D"2"></rect>
